Explanations on global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report (Competitiveness Report) for the year 2001.
In the study that covers 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy the top three positions, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe lag behind.
(All rankings can be read at www.weforum.com).
As one of the co-leaders of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also an economic competition among countries besides military competition?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is precisely defined: namely as the ability of a country to achieve sustained economic growth over a medium-term period – that is, within a five-year timeframe.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries in the world could achieve higher growth simultaneously.
Nevertheless, it makes sense to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Every country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep up with those of other countries regarding their ability to achieve sustained economic growth.
In some ways, economic growth can be compared to a sporting competition where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries compete, for example, for internationally mobile capital.
The more a country can attract foreign direct investment, the less another country will get.
This becomes clear when countries compete for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce, and often includes offers such as tax breaks, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to local technical university study programs.
This year, we assessed a country's competitiveness (growth capacity) using three broad criteria: (1) technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated average values using a specific method to then create a general growth and competitiveness index.
The criterion Technology refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and utilize technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and thus achieve high values in terms of innovation.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and consequently achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Countries that are innovative benefit from these innovations and enjoy a high standard of living as well.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three positions on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts unbiased and impartial?
Can one trust that the government fulfills its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and deteriorating judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are globally leading, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also at the top of the list.
Corruption is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
As we learned from Asia in the late 1990s, a macroeconomic crisis can undermine economic growth, even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries regarding macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: those that are innovative and those that are not innovative.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, an excellent system of technological innovation is considered a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
The universities must be outstanding, state laboratories should have world-class standards, and both government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher education and universities after completing their compulsory schooling.
In the USA and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovative" countries, technology is equally important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad rather than developed within the country itself.
Some countries specialize in importing new technologies, while others do so to a lesser extent.
In the past ten or fifteen years, a large part of technology imports has occurred through foreign direct investment.
American firms that invested heavily in Mexico or Taiwanese firms that invested on the Chinese mainland brought new technologies as well, which increased production efficiency in the respective target economy.
Therefore, it was certainly worthwhile for these countries to pursue such foreign investments enthusiastically: they bring not only capital but also new technologies.
A strength and weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore ironic that many of the countries that topped the list this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in recession, while other lower-ranked countries, such as China (ranked 39th), are not affected by the global recession.
Partially, the slowdown of the economy is connected to the terrorist attacks on September 11th, but it is also increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies linked to it through trade and production networks were sliding into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the USA will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth in the next five years.
